{
  "doc_id": "55400",
  "text": "Cell behavior is ultimately dictated by the complement of mRNAs that are expressed in the cell. In addition to generating hypotheses, global analysis of gene expression can be used as a way to phenotype cells and is now routinely used to classify breast cancer subtypes [CITATION_1] . Expression microarrays are the most common method used for this type of gene analysis. More recently, ultra-high throughput sequencing has been used to analyze the entire transcriptome within a cell. The advantages of mRNA sequencing (RNA-seq) include the ability to obtain more comprehensive coverage relative to microarrays and the identifi-cation of specific splice variants of a particular gene [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . This is in addition to being able to determine the presence and amount of each mRNA relative to another sequenced sample. Recently, RNA-seq has become more cost effective than microarray and analysis of the huge amounts of data generated from each experiment has become standardized making RNA-seq a feasible way to study the mechanisms of cell behavior.",
  "correct_citation": {
